Comments.Message:
Hi,

The issue you're experiencing could be caused by the fact that the themes you're mentioning apply styles to instances of the MenuItem class, not to the classes that inherit from it. When you add views to your MenuItem Region, you might be adding an object that inherits from the MenuItem class (exemplified by the code below):

public partial class SomeMenuItem : MenuItem
{
  public SomeMenuItem
  {
    InitializeComponent();
  }
}

(this assumes there is a xaml file associated to it, as you would generally do when creating a View)

In that case, the theme won't apply, since the object that you're adding to your region is an instance of SomeMenuItem, not MenuItem.

If you, for example, registered a MenuItem instance with your region, the theme for the item would be displayed correctly. An example of what I'm saying would be something like this:

regionViewRegistry.RegisterViewWithRegion("SomeRegion", () => new MenuItem() {Header = "MenuItem in Region"});

Another alternative would be to modify the theme in order to make it apply the styles to the items of your views' types.

I hope you find this helpful.

Guido Leandro Maliandi
http://blogs.southworks.net/gmaliandi
